rship contest}}\n{{Infobox election\n| election_name = Next Conservative leadership election\n| country = Canada\n| type = primary\n| vote_type = Popular <!-- default -->\n| ongoing = yes\n| previous_election = 2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election\n| previous_year = 2017\n| election_date = To be announced\n| votes_for_election = \n| opinion_polls = #Opinion polling\n| image_upright = <!--        ONLY VERIFIED CONTESTANTS BELONG HERE.       -->\n| image1 = [[File:LeslynLewis-HEADSHOT1-lg.jpg|160x160px]]\n| image1_size = 180x180px\n| colour1 = {{Canadian party colour|CA|Conservative|nohash}}\n| candidate1 = [[#Leslyn Lewis|Leslyn Lewis]]\n| image2 = [[File:Peter MacKay crop (cropped).JPG|160x160px]]\n| image2_size = 180x180px\n| colour2 = {{Canadian party colour|CA|Conservative|nohash}}\n| candidate2 = [[Peter MacKay]]\n| image4 = [[File:Erin O'Toole (cropped).jpg|160x160px]]\n| image4_size = 180x180px\n| colour4 = {{Canadian party colour|CA|Conservative|nohash}}\n| candidate4 = [[Erin O'Toole]]\n| image5 = [[File:Dereksloan2110.jpg|160x160px]]\n| image5_size = 180x180px\n| colour5 = {{Canadian party colour|CA|Conservative|nohash}}\n| candidate5 = [[Derek Sloan]]\n| map_image = Canada Federal Ridings Map.svg\n| map_caption = Map of Canada by constituency\n}}\n\n{{Infobox Canadian leadership election\n| party    = Conservative\n| colour   = {{Canadian party colour|CA|Conservative}}\n| year     = 2020\n| logo     = \n| location = [[Toronto Congress Centre]]<ref name=\"PlattJan\"/>\n| date     = TBA\n| winner   =\n| replaces = [[Andrew Scheer]]\n| numcands = 4\n| ballots  = \n| entryfee = $300,000 <small>(of which $100,000 is a refundable compliance deposit)<ref name=\":2\"/></small>\n| spendcap = \n|}}\n\nThe '''Next Conservative Party of Canada leadership election''' will be held at an as-yet-undetermined date and location<ref name=\":5\" /> to choose a successor to [[Andrew Scheer]], who announced his pending resignation as leader of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]].<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/conservative-leadership-vote-scheer-1.5414024 | title=Conservatives to pick their new leader on June 27 &#124; CBC News}}</ref> The $200,000 non-refundable entrance fee also makes it the most expensive leadership race ever in Canadian politics.<ref>{{cite news | url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/grenier-conservative-leadership-fee-1.5427808 | title=Conservative leadership fee makes this the most expensive race ever \u2014 but is it worth the price? &#124; CBC News}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 March 2020, the party suspended activities pertaining to the leadership race due to the ongoing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|coronavirus pandemic crisis in Canada]].<ref name=\":5\" /> Party officials said they would revisit their decision on 1 May 2020.<ref name=\":5\" />\n\n==Timeline==\n===2019===\n*October 21 \u2013 The [[2019 Canadian federal election]] was held. The Conservatives remained in opposition against a minority [[Liberal Party of Canada|Liberal]] government.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Cecco |first1=Leyland |title=Canada elections: Trudeau wins narrow victory to form minority government |url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/oct/22/canada-elections-justin-trudeau-wins-narrow-victory-to-form-minority-government |access-date=12 December 2019 |work=The Guardian |date=22 October 2019}}</ref> Under CPC rules, a loss in an election triggers an automatic leadership review. \n*October 22 \u2013 CPC Leader [[Andrew Scheer]] announced he will continue as leader.<ref>{{cite news |title=Andrew Scheer says he's staying on as leader, will fight Trudeau in the next election |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/andrew-scheer-staying-on-leader-1.5330762 |publisher=CBC News |date= 22 October 2019 |access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref>\n*December 12 \u2013 Andrew Scheer announced his pending resignation as leader of the Conservatives.<ref>{{cite news |last1=Tunney |first1=Catherine |last2=Harris |first2=Kathleen |title=Andrew Scheer stepping down as Conservative Party leader |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/scheer-resigns-1.5393803 |access-date=12 December 2019 |publisher=CBC News |date=12 December 2019}}</ref>\n*December 21 \u2013 The party executive announced that a national party policy convention scheduled for mid-April 2020 has been postponed until November \"so greater focus could be given to the details and organization around the Conservative leadership election process.\"<ref>{{cite news |title=Conservatives postpone convention by 7 months to focus on leadership race |url=https://www.ctvnews.ca/politics/conservatives-postpone-convention-by-7-months-to-focus-on-leadership-race-1.4740245 |accessdate=24 December 2019 |work=CTV News |agency=The Canadian Press |date=21 December 2019}}</ref>\n*December 24 \u2013 The party announced that former Deputy Leader [[Lisa Raitt]] will co-chair the organizing committee for the leadership race.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6336742/lisa-raitt-find-replacement/|title=Former MP Lisa Raitt to help run Conservative leadership race|date=24 December 2019|website=Global News|url-status=live|access-date=25 December 2019|agency=The Canadian Press}}</ref> Dan Nowlan is the committee's other co-chair.<ref name=\"PlattJan\">{{cite news |last1=Platt |first1=Brian |title=Federal Conservatives set leadership vote for June 27, opting for shortened race |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/federal-conservatives-set-leadership-vote-for-june-27-opting-for-shortened-race |accessdate=3 January 2020 |work=National Post |date=3 January 2020}}</ref>\n===2020===\n*January 13 \u2013 Leadership election process officially commences.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cath_cullen/status/1216179131509104640|title=NEW: The Conservative Party of Canada has announced it will officially open its leadership election on Monday, Jan 13. Candidates will have until the end of February to apply.|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=11 January 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.conservative.ca/conservative-leadership-election-to-open-january-13/|title=Conservative Leadership election to open January 13|date=12 January 2020|website=Conservative Party of Canada|access-date=12 January 2020}}</ref><ref name=\":3\">{{cite news|url=https://globalnews.ca/news/6400159/conservative-leadership-race-rules/|title=Conservative leadership race officially kicks off Monday now that the rules are set|date=11 January 2020|website=Global News|access-date=12 January 2020|agency=The Canadian Press}}</ref>\n*February 27 \u2013 Deadline for potential candidates to enter leadership election. Candidates must have, by this date, paid at least $25,000 towards their registration fee and submitted signatures of at least 1,000 party members qualified to nominate them for leader.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cath_cullen/status/1216181709835853825|title=But right out of the gate, anyone who wants to become an \"approved applicant\" needs $25K and 1,000 signatures by Feb 27.|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=11 January 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n*March 25 \u2013 Deadline for candidates to meet all entry requirements, including having paid the $300,000 entrance fee and compliance deposit in full and collected signatures of 3,000 qualified party members from 30 Electoral District Associations, in at least seven provinces or territories.<ref name=\":2\" /><ref name=\":3\" /><ref name=\"rules\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/cath_cullen/status/1216181128052334598|title=Candidates will need a total of $200,000 in a non-refundable registration fee, a $100,000 compliance deposit and 3,000 signatures from party members- due by March 25.|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=11 January 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|access-date=11 January 2020}}</ref>\n*March 26 \u2013 Leadership race suspended indefinitely due to ongoing [[2020 coronavirus pandemic in Canada|coronavirus pandemic crisis]].<ref name=\":5\">{{Cite news|last=Canadian Press|first=The|url=https://www.nationalnewswatch.com/2020/03/26/canadian-press-newsalert-conservatives-suspend-partys-leadership-race/|title=Conservatives suspend party's leadership race in face of COVID-19 crisis|date=26 March 2020|work=National Newswatch|access-date=26 March 2020|url-status=live}}</ref> Party officials said that the schedule for the debates and leadership convention would be revisited on 1 May 2020.<ref name=\":5\" />\n*May 15 \u2013 New deadline to sign up as a member for purposes of voting in the leadership race. Previous deadline was 17 April 2020.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/SeanPrevil/status/1243368424409096194|title=#BREAKING: The Conservative Party has announced it is suspending the leadership race. It says the scheduled debates in April and the leadership event on June 27 are cancelled. New dates to be determined May 1 Membership deadline moved to May 15. #CPCLdr #cdnpoli #COVID19|last=Previl|first=Sean|date=26 March 2020|website=Twitter|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=26 March 2020}}</ref>\n*TBA \u2013 Conservative Party of Canada Leadership Convention. Previous date for the convention was 27 June 2020.\n\n==Rules and procedures==\nOn January 11, 2020, the party's Leadership Election Organizing Committee released the Rules and Procedures for the 2020 Leadership document.<ref name=\":2\"/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://cpcassets.conservative.ca/wp-content/uploads/2020/01/11202248/15affbc9396545c.pdf|title=Rules and Procedures for the 2020 Leadership|last=|first=|date=January 11, 2020|website=Conservative Party of Canada|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=February 3, 2020}}</ref> It confirmed the vote would be held under [[Instant-runoff voting|instant-runoff voting]], open to those who are members of the Conservative Party of Canada as of April 17. (This date was later pushed back to May 15.) To appear on the ballot, a member must apply to the Leadership Candidate Nomination Committee between January 13 and February 27, with 1,000 signatures of endorsement from party members (which must span at least 30 Electoral Districts in 7 provinces),<ref name=\"rules\"/> a $25,000 installment of the registration fee and a completed 42-page Leadership Contestant Questionnaire, which requires them to declare they accept \"the policies, principles, goals and objectives\" of the Conservative Party.<ref name=\"Plattdecarie2\"/> If approved by the Committees, the applicant has until March 25 to provide the remainder of the 3,000 endorsement signatures and $200,000 registration fee.<ref name=\":3\" /> In addition a $100,000 Compliance Deposit is required prior to March 25 but is returned upon completing required financial filings and adhering to Rules and Procedures document. As in the [[2017 Conservative Party of Canada leadership election|2017 leadership election]], each electoral district is given 100 points which are distributed according to weight of a candidate's vote in that electoral distribute, with the first candidate receiving 16,901 points winning the contest.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/grenier-conservative-leadership-1.5424860|title=How the Conservatives' leadership rules could limit the field this time|last=Grenier|first=\u00c9ric|date=January 14, 2020|work=CBC News|access-date=February 3, 2020|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Candidates==\nVerified candidates are authorized contestants that have paid the full $200,000 registration fee, the entire $100,000 compliance deposit, and submitted all 3,000 required signatures of endorsement by March 25, 2020. Verified candidates have secured their name on the leadership ballot.<ref name=\"qual\">[https://s3-us-west-2.amazonaws.com/cpc-leadership/wp-content/uploads/2020/02/12153525/Chart_EN.pdf Leadership Entry Requirements], Conservative Part of Canada, retorved 26 March 2020</ref><ref name=\"cand\">{{cite web |title=Candidates |url=https://cpc-leadership2020.ca/candidates/ |website=Conservative Party of Canada |publisher=Conservative Party of Canada |accessdate=February 26, 2020}}</ref>\n\n===Leslyn Lewis ===\n[[File:LeslynLewis-HEADSHOT1-lg.jpg|thumb|upright|Leslyn Lewis]]\n;Background \nLeslyn Lewis is a Toronto lawyer and the former CPC candidate for [[Scarborough\u2014Rouge Park]], [[Ontario]] in the [[2015 Canadian federal election|2015 election]].<ref name=\"sun\">{{cite web|url=https://torontosun.com/news/local-news/warmington-toronto-lawyer-sets-sights-on-conservative-leadership|title=WARMINGTON: Toronto lawyer sets sights on Conservative leadership &#124; Toronto Sun|date=23 January 2020}}</ref> She holds a bachelor's degree from University of Toronto, two master's degrees, a law degree from [[Osgoode Hall Law School]]<ref name=\"auto4\">{{cite web|url=https://www.hamiltonnews.com/news-story/9839237-toronto-lawyer-leslyn-lewis-could-make-canadian-political-history-in-conservative-leadership-race/|title=Toronto lawyer Leslyn Lewis could make Canadian political history in Conservative leadership race|first=Kevin|last=Werner|date=1 February 2020|website=HamiltonNews.com}}</ref> and a PhD in International Law.<ref name=\"sun\"/> She is also a Vice Chair of the Ontario Trillium Foundation and Chair of the Partnership Committee.<ref name=\"auto4\"/>\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 22 January 2020<ref name=\"auto2\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/permalink.php?story_fbid=472441373471726&id=253958051986727|title=Bobby For Canada - Conservative Party of Canada - Scarborough Rouge Park|website=facebook.com}}</ref>\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' [http://leslynlewis.ca Leslyn Lewis]\n;Policies:\n:;Economic\n:*Abolish the carbon tax<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Repeal Bill C-69 (\"The modernization of the National Energy Board and Canadian Environmental Assessment Agency\") and C-48 (\"An Act respecting the regulation of vessels that transport crude oil or persistent oil\") to promote pipeline construction<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:;Foreign\n:*Withdraw from the UN [[Global Compact for Migration]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Move Canada's embassy in [[Israel]] to Jerusalem<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Redirect money from foreign aid to providing Indigenous reserves with clean drinking water<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Remove abortion funding from foreign aid<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:;Social\n:*Protect free speech by opposing Bill C-16 (which adds gender expression and gender identity as protected grounds to the Canadian Human Rights Act) and C-8 (which bans [[conversion therapy]], the pseudoscientific practice of trying to change an individual's sexual orientation from homosexual or bisexual to heterosexual using psychological or spiritual interventions.)<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Increase criminal penalties for human trafficking<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Ban sex-selective abortions<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Increase funding for pregnancy centres<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Review firearm laws and reduce bureaucracy<ref>{{cite web |title=I\u2019ve been listening to Party members who care deeply about this issue. Their message is clear: it\u2019s time for a complete review of Canada\u2019s firearms laws to make sure they are actually contributing to public safety, and not just building Ottawa bureaucracy.|last1=Lewis |first1=Dr. Leslyn |url=https://twitter.com/LeslynLewis/status/1241345862548312064 |website=Twitter |accessdate=6 April 2020 |language=en |date=21 March 2020}}</ref><br>\n:*Free votes for MPs on conscience issues<ref>{{cite web |title=Policies |url=https://www.leslynlewis.ca/policies |website=Leslyn Lewis |accessdate=6 April 2020}}</ref><br>\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Leslyn Lewis\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n*[[Richard Bragdon]] (MP for [[Tobique\u2014Mactaquac]])<ref name=\"Bragdon\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/RichardBragdon/status/1246232352642215936|title=I am proud to endorse Dr. Leslyn Lewis to be our next leader of the Conservative Party of Canada|author=Richard Bragdon MP|date=3 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n*[[Rosemarie Falk]] (MP for [[Battlefords\u2014Lloydminster]])<ref name=\"Falk\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LeslynLewis/status/1246474070004121602|title=Rosemarie Falk Endorses Leslyn Lewis|date=4 April 2020|access-date=4 April 2020|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n*[[Tamara Jansen]] (MP for [[Cloverdale\u2014Langley City]])<ref name=\"Jansen\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LeslynLewis/status/1246866618724032514|title=Tamara Jansen Endorses Leslyn Lewis|date=5 April 2020|access-date=5 April 2020|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n*[[Cathay Wagantall]] (MP for [[Yorkton\u2014Melville]])<ref name=\"Wagantall\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LeslynLewis/status/1248251024696954880|title=Cathay Wagantall Endorses Leslyn Lewis|date=9 April 2020|access-date=9 April 2020|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n*[[Jeremy Patzer]] (MP for [[Cypress Hills\u2014Grasslands]])<ref name=\"Patzer\">{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/LeslynLewis/status/1251298781871693824|title=Jeremy Patzer Endorses Leslyn Lewis|date=17 April 2020|access-date=17 April 2020|website=Twitter}}</ref>\n;'''Senators:'''\n;'''Provincial & territorial politicians:'''\n*[[Patterk Netser]] ([[Legislative Assembly of Nunavut|Nunavut MLA]] for [[Aivilik]], former [[Legislative Assembly of Nunavut|MLA]] for [[Nanulik]] 2004-2008)<ref name=\"Netser\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LeslynLewisCPC/posts/146756743526415|title=Patterk Netser Endorses Leslyn Lewis|date=18 April 2020|access-date=18 April 2020|website=Facebook}}</ref>\n;'''Municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Former MPs:'''\n*[[Brad Trost]] (MP for [[Saskatoon\u2014University]], 2004\u20132019)<ref name=\"Trost\">{{cite news |last1=Trost |first1=Brad |title=In an attempt to favour Peter McKay, Richard Decarie was blocked from entering the CPC Leadership Race.|url=https://twitter.com/BradTrostCPC/status/1234291935734632449|date=1 March 2020|access-date=5 March 2020|agency=Twitter}}</ref>\n*[[Reed Elley]] (Former MP for [[Nanaimo\u2014Cowichan]], 1997-2004)<ref name=\"Elley\">{{cite web|url=https://www.facebook.com/LeslynLewisCPC/posts/147665123435577|title=Reed Elley Endorses Leslyn Lewis|date=21 April 2020|access-date=21 April 2020|website=Facebook}}</ref>\n;'''Former Senators:'''\n;'''Former provincial politicians:'''\n;'''Former municipal politicians:'''\n;'''Other prominent individuals:''' \n*[[Charles McVety]], president of [[Canada Christian College]]<ref name=\"plattjan\">{{cite news |last1=Platt |first1=Brian |title=Social conservatives look to wield influence \u2014 again \u2014 on Conservative leadership race |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/politics/social-conservatives-look-to-wield-influence-again-on-conservative-leadership-race |accessdate=January 29, 2020 |work=National Post |date=January 29, 2020}}</ref>\n;'''Organizations:\n*[[Campaign Life Coalition]]<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/CampaignLife/status/1220427815784517632?s=20|title=CLC has met @LeslynLewis and will be proud to endorse her for leader|date=23 January 2020|language=en|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>'''\n;'''Media:'''\n}}\n\n===Peter MacKay===\n[[File:Peter MacKay crop.JPG|thumb|upright|Peter MacKay]]\n;Background\n[[Peter MacKay]], {{age|1965|9|27}}, was the MP for [[Central Nova]] (2004\u20132015), and for [[Pictou\u2014Antigonish\u2014Guysborough]] (1997\u20132004). He was [[Minister of Justice (Canada)|Minister of Justice and Attorney General]] (2013\u20132015), [[Minister of National Defence (Canada)|Minister of National Defense]] (2007\u20132013), [[Minister of Foreign Affairs (Canada)|Minister of Foreign Affairs]] (2006\u20132007), Deputy Leader of the [[Conservative Party of Canada]] (2004\u20132015). He was the leader of the [[Progressive Conservative Party of Canada]] (2003) at the time of the merger. Prior to entering politics, MacKay worked as a lawyer.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thestar.com/politics/federal/2019/12/13/erin-otoole-and-peter-mackay-are-preparing-to-enter-the-race-to-replace-andrew-scheer.html|title=Erin O'Toole and Peter MacKay are preparing to enter the race to replace Andrew Scheer|last=Boutilier|first=Alex|date=13 December 2019|website=The Star|access-date=13 December 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"starpros\" />\n\n:'''Candidacy announced:''' 15 January 2020<ref name=\":4\">{{Cite news|url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/politics/mackay-tweets-leadership-1.5427544|title='I'm in': Peter MacKay confirms he's running for the Conservative leadership|last=Cullen|first=Catherine|date=15 January 2020|work=CBC|access-date=15 January 2020}}</ref>\n:'''Date registered with Elections Canada:'''\n:'''Campaign website:''' [http://www.petermackay.ca www.petermackay.ca]\n;Policies:\n:;Economic\n:*No Limit Tax-Free RRSP withdrawal for first time home buyers<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://petermackay.ca/en-CA/rrsp-reer|title=No Limit Tax-Free RRSP Withdrawal &#124; Peter MacKay|website=petermackay.ca}}</ref><br>\n:*Abolish the carbon tax<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://petermackay.ca/en-CA/no-carbon-tax-taxe-carbone|title=End the Carbon Tax &#124; Peter MacKay|website=petermackay.ca}}</ref><br>\n:*Repeal Bill C-69 (\"The modernization of the National Energy Board and Canadian Environmental Assessment Agency\") and C-48 (\"An Act respecting the regulation of vessels that transport crude oil or persistent oil\")<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://petermackay.ca/en-CA/government-blockades-blocus-gouvernement|title=Stop the Government Blockades &#124; Peter MacKay|website=petermackay.ca}}</ref>\n:;Foreign\n:*Prevent [[Huawei]] from entering Canada's 5G Networks<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://petermackay.ca/en-CA/huawei|title=No Huawei in 5G Networks &#124; Peter MacKay|website=petermackay.ca}}</ref><br>\n:;Military\n:*Meet the 2% of GDP targets for defence spending set out by [[NATO]]<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://petermackay.ca/en-CA/nato-otan|title=Meet NATO Spending Target &#124; Peter MacKay|website=petermackay.ca}}</ref><br>\n:;Social\n:MacKay is pro-choice and supports [[same-sex marriage]].  Following the 2019 federal election, he was critical of Andrew Scheer's handing of the issues of abortion and same-sex marriage, saying that the issues had held the party back.<ref>{{cite news |last1=The Canadian Press |title=Peter MacKay regrets how 'stinking albatross' comments were viewed |url=https://www.cbc.ca/news/canada/saskatchewan/peter-mackay-regina-visit-1.5489675 |accessdate=March 26, 2020 |work=[[CBC News]] |date=March 6, 2020|author1-link=The Canadian Press }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Taylor |first1=Stephanie |title=Peter MacKay regrets how his 'stinking albatross' comment after federal election was 'misconstrued' |url=https://nationalpost.com/news/peter-mackay-says-he-regrets-how-stinking-albatross-comment-was-viewed |accessdate=March 19, 2020 |work=National Post |date=March 6, 2020}}</ref>\n\n{{Endorsements box\n|df=yes| title = Endorsements of Peter MacKay\n| list =\n;'''MPs:'''\n*[[Ziad Aboultaif]] (MP for [[Edmonton Manning]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ziad_aboultaif/status/1220481336680402944?s=20|title=Proud to put my support behind @PeterMackay for #CPCLDR. |last=Aboultaif|first=Ziad|date=23 January 2020|website=@ziad_aboultaif|language=en|access-date=23 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Scott Aitchison]] (MP for [[Parry Sound\u2014Muskoka]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mymuskokanow.com/97703/peter-mackay-endorsement-for-conservative-party-leader/|title=Peter MacKay endorsement for Conservative Party Leader|last=Shubet|first=Nathan|date=27 January 2020|website=|language=en|access-date=31 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Dean Allison]] (MP for [[Niagara West]]; Shadow Minister for International Trade)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/DeanAllisonMP/status/1219662403887124482|title=I'm happy to announce that I'm supporting @PeterMacKay|last=Allison|first=Dean|date=21 January 2020|website=@DeanAllisonMP|language=en|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Tony Baldinelli]] (MP for [[Niagara Falls (electoral district)|Niagara Falls]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/Tony_Baldinelli/status/1224327098107670534?s=19|title=I am proud to announce my endorsement of @PeterMacKay|last=Baldinelli|first=Tony|date=3 February 2020|language=en|access-date=3 February 2020}}</ref>\n*[[John Barlow (Canadian politician)|John Barlow]] (MP for [[Foothills (electoral district)|Foothills]])<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://twitter.com/JohnBarlowMP/status/1239386704680607744|title=I am announcing my support of @PeterMacKay for #CPC Leader.|first=John|last=Barlow|date=15 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Luc Berthold]] (MP for [[M\u00e9gantic\u2014L'\u00c9rable]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.lapresse.ca/actualites/politique/202001/23/01-5257954-direction-du-pcc-peter-mackay-obtient-lappui-de-deux-deputes-du-quebec.php|title=Direction du PCC : Peter MacKay obtient l'appui de deux d\u00e9put\u00e9s du Qu\u00e9bec|last=Bellavance|first=Jo\u00ebl-Denis|date=23 January 2020|language=fr|access-date=24 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[James Bezan]] (MP for [[Selkirk\u2014Interlake\u2014Eastman]]) <ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/jamesbezan/status/1221095128594616326|title=I like what I'm hearing from @PeterMacKay.|first=James|last=Bezan|date=25 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Blaine Calkins]] (MP for [[Red Deer-Lacombe]], Chairman of the Standing Committee on Access to Information, Privacy and Ethics)<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/blainecalkinsmp/status/1217849052676554753|title=I'm supporting Peter MacKay!|last=Calkins|first=Blaine|date=16 January 2020|website=@BlaineCalkinsMP|language=en|access-date=16 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Colin Carrie]] (MP for [[Oshawa (electoral district)|Oshawa]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ColinCarrieCPC/status/1220071385550204930?s=20|title=I'm pleased to endorse my friend @PeterMacKay as our Party's next Leader.|last=Carrie|first=Colin|date=22 January 2020|website=@ColinCarrieCPC|language=en|access-date=22 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Michael Cooper (politician)|Michael Cooper]] (MP for [[St. Albert\u2014Edmonton]])<ref>{{cite web|url = https://twitter.com/Cooper4SAE/status/1235236031483375616|title = I\u2019m proud to endorse @PeterMacKay for leader|access-date = 15 April 2020|last = Cooper|first = Michael|author-link= Michael Cooper (politician)|work =[[Twitter]] |date = 4 March 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Scot Davidson]] (MP for [[York-Simcoe]])<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/ScotDavidsonMP/status/1219694124728754176|title=Proud to support @PeterMacKay for @CPC_HQ leader.|last=Davidson|first=Scot|date=21 January 2020|website=@ScotDavidsonMP|language=en|access-date=21 January 2020}}</ref>\n*[[Chris d'Entremont]] (MP for [[West Nova]])<ref>{{cite we